To reproduce: Write the following code in a new Console App (.Net Core):

```C#
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

namespace WatchBug
{
    class Program
    {
        public static async Task Main(string[] args)
        {
            foreach (var module in new List<object> { new object() })
            {
                new List<object>().FirstOrDefault(x => module != null);
            }

            foreach (var module in new List<object> { new object() })
            {
                module.ToString();
                new List<object>().FirstOrDefault(x => module != null);
            }
        }
    }
}
```
Put a breakepoint on the line &quot;module. ToString()&quot;.
Hover over the variable module. Observe that it does not show a popup as usual.
Look at the Locals window. Observe that module is listed as an exception: &quot;'module' threw an exception of type 'System.NullReferenceException'&quot;
Add &quot;module&quot; as a watch: Observe that it is listed as an exception again.

Expected behaviour is to be able to see the variable's value with the above methods.
Note that the code runs fine, it is just the debugging that doesn't.

